<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0815-A"><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Nelson said that the details of his plan remain fluid, but that it would leave the filibuster rules intact while confirming more of Bush's nominees than Reid has said his party can accept.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>The attempt to force a vote on his nominaton drew fewer than 50 votes.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Senator Ben Nelson, a Nebraska Democrat who is among the leaders of the group seeking a compromise, emerged from the meeting saying they were drawing close to a deal but remained short of persuading the six Democrats and six Republicans they need to seal the deal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;It would be a fundamental part of any compromise that the nuclear option be off the table,&quot; said Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>The aide spoke on condition of anonymity because the scenario was preliminary.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>(Optional add end)</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>At the same time, he met with leaders of outside groups during the day, and a representative of one organization who attended said he did not reject the terms, either.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Democrats quickly denounced McConnell's proposal.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>A: David McKeague, Richard Griffin, Henry Saad, William G. Myers III, Janice Rogers Brown, William H. Pryor Jr. and Priscilla Owen.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Democrats prevented final votes on 10 of Bush's first-term appeals court nominees, and have threatened to do the same this year to seven whom the president renominated.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Senate Republicans on Tuesday rebuffed a Democratic overture aimed at ending a confrontation over federal judges, saying that any agreement must include a pledge not to filibuster future nominees -- especially Supreme Court nominees.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="14,44"><scu uid="43" label="Republicans dismissed a Democratic proposal" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>&quot;If anything, her decisions since then only confirm that she should not receive a life-time position on the 5th Circuit.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>&quot;She has a vitriolic hostility to government,&quot; said Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Currently, 60 votes are needed to end a filibuster and force a confirmation vote; Republicans want to lower the threshold to 51 votes for judicial nominees.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="21"><scu uid="30" label="Republican leaders threatened to rule out the filibuster [in judicial confirmations]." weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>At issue is the filibuster, a parliamentary device that can be overcome only by a majority of 60 votes or higher in the 100-member Senate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Democrats describe the rules change as a &quot;nuclear option&quot; and are threatening to slow down Senate business if Republicans persist.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Although Democrats filibustered his nomination in the past, they have signaled that they will not do so again.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>For their part, Democrats said they would accept no agreement that restricted future use of the filibuster, leaving the two sides at an impasse.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>&quot;I don't think that's a new phenomenon here.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Democrats point to Supreme Court Justice Abe Fortas, who was blocked from becoming chief justice in what the Senate historian's Web site calls &quot;the first filibuster in Senate history on a Supreme Court nomination.&quot;</line><line>A: The Republican party is talking about seeking a parliamentary ruling that declares filibusters are not permitted against judicial nominees.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line><line>It is derived from the Dutch word vrijbuiter, or free booter, and the Spanish filibustero.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Two days later, the Senate will hold a vote on the motion, known as &quot;cloture,&quot; which requires 60 votes.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>In return, the aide said, Reid asked for a Republican commitment not to change the filibuster rules, along with promises to re-instate Judiciary committee procedures that would permit senators to block nominations during the committee vetting process.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>They are planning a series of public events to state opposition to the judges, and to any rules change that would make their confirmations possible.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>A: It depends on who you ask.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Democrats are fighting back by citing inflammatory statements and decisions handed down by Owen and Rogers Brown.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Owen and Brown, the two judges at the heart of the Republican campaign against the filibuster, were in Washington Tuesday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>In an interview with USA Today published Tuesday, White House deputy chief of staff Karl Rove said the White House did not support a compromise on judicial filibusters.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Her supporters dismiss those characterizations as groundless, describing the former Houston attorney as fair-minded and more than qualified.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Frist and Reid reached their self-declared dead end at the same time a small group of Democrats, who have been meeting with Republicans also eager to avoid a showdown, floated a proposal to clear the way for confirmation of some of Bush's blocked appointees.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Cheney is expected to uphold the motion, Democrats are expected to object, and the chamber will vote on whether to table, or reject, the Democratic appeal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>If the rule change on the filibuster passes, it would clear the way for all of the Bush nominees to have up-or-down votes on their appointments.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: Who are the judicial nominees involved in the filibuster controversy?</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;This is a way to cure that.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Nelson's spokesman, David DiMartino, declined to confirm the details of the compromise offer.</line><line>Vote counters on both sides have sad they expect Sen. Olympia Snowe of Maine to do likewise.</line><line>Democrats would also clear the way for final votes on William H. Pryor Jr. for the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals and Janice Rogers Brown for the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="12,13,36,37,42"><scu uid="6" label="Brown nomination was to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals of District of Columbia" weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>Nebraska Sen. Ben Nelson, a Democrat seeking re-election in a Republican state, outlined the suggested compromise for Frist on Sunday night at a dinner at the Tennessee Republican's home.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>The Senate Judiciary Committee on Thursday approved and sent to the full Senate two of President Bush's candidates for seats on the federal appeals bench.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Republicans hold 55 seats in the 100-member Senate, so six GOP defectors would be enough to deny Frist a majority vote on the filibuster issue.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>If Republicans leave the right to filibuster judges intact, Reid has said, his caucus will let them pick one appellate court nominee for a non-filibustered confirmation from a group the Democrats have strongly criticized: Janice Rogers Brown of California, William Myers III of Idaho, Priscilla Owen of Texas and William Pryor Jr. of Alabama.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="22" label="Democrats opposed Brown's nomination." weight="1"/><scu uid="29" label="Senate leaders negotiated over judicial nominations procedure" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>But Republicans said Democrats have a history of labeling mainstream conservatives as extremists.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>It remained unclear Tuesday whether Frist would sign off on such a deal, however.</line><line>WASHINGTON - Moderate Democratic and Republican senators met into the evening Tuesday night in the hopes of avoiding a showdown over filibusters of judicial nominees, as Republican leaders planned to launch a carefully choreographed debate on the issue of judges Wednesday that they hope will bring public opinion to their side.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="0,11,41"><scu uid="35" label="Moderate Democratic and Republican senators tried to work out a compromise" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Democrats said that she would use the bench to advance &quot;extremist&quot; conservative views, but Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., countered that the jurist is independent and hard-working, &quot;with an open mind&quot; and &quot;a lot of common sense.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Sen Patrick J. Leahy of Vermont, the committee's ranking Democrat, said Owen had shown herself to be &quot;an ends-oriented activist judge&quot; in Texas.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>The two were blocked by threatened Democratic filibusters during the last session of Congress.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Owen is a favorite of abortion opponents and religious conservatives because of several legal opinions she wrote denying minors the right to an abortion without parental notification.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>The other nominees pending before the full Senate are California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown, Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen -- a favorite among conservative activists -- and William Myers, a former ranching and mining lobbyist.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="12,19,36,37,42,48,6"><scu uid="6" label="Brown nomination was to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals of District of Columbia" weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Democrats previously used filibusters to block the nominations of Owen and Brown and have said they would seek to do so again, setting the stage for the Senate showdown.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Nelson said in an interview that his biggest challenge is to find a compromise &quot;without undermining the leaders in both caucuses.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>In 1957 Strom Thurmond launched the longest one-man filibuster in history, speaking for more than 24 hours to block the Civil Rights Act of 1957.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Frist, R-Tenn., said he intends to bring the first of several of Bush's nominations to the Senate floor for a vote after the chamber passes a transportation funding bill, which is expected by the end of this week.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>By opposing unanimous consent requests from Republicans, Democrats can block or delay most of what the Senate does.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>&quot;It's about clearing the way for a Supreme Court nominee who only needs 51 votes, not 60,&quot; for confirmation.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Wade decision legalizing abortion if 60 votes are needed to win confirmation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Republicans plan to stretch debate over several days and make a show of trying to cut the Democrats off through normal procedures, a move intended to highlight the perception of Democratic obstructionism, Republican senators said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Frist rejected the offer again Tuesday, saying this &quot;is a matter of principle, and the principle is this fairness of an up-or-down vote&quot; for all nominees.</line><line>Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., has said the ability to filibuster judicial nominees, now or in the future, must end.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>That's not a compromise at all,&quot; said Schumer.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>But both men rejected elements of Nelson's plan Tuesday and signaled that they want a showdown vote on the filibuster issue -- often called &quot;the nuclear option&quot; -- as early as next week, if not Friday.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Moderate Democrats and Republicans failed Tuesday to derail a confrontation over federal judgeships that both sides said would begin playing out Wednesday on the floor of the Senate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Schumer said he was &quot;proud to oppose this nomination.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>To win confirmation, they would need 51 votes in the 100-seat Senate.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="18,32,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Social conservatives fear Bush would pick a Supreme Court candidate who doesn't oppose the Supreme Court's Roe v.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>It protects our democracy and the independence of our federal courts, it protects the American people and lets us do their business, and it breaks a partisan stalemate that is unnecessary and divisive,&quot; Reid said in remarks on the Senate floor.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>He suggested starting with Thomas Griffith, who Bush has picked to serve on the Court of Appeals for the District of Columbia.</line><line>Griffith is one of the four nominees pending before the Senate.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>That means all 100 senators agree on issues like skipping the full reading of every bill, allowing committees to meet while the Senate is in session and voting on procedural Senate business.</line><line>Passing a bill or confirming a nominee requires only a simple majority, 51 senators if all 100 senators are present.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>McConnell acknowledged that Republicans had stalled many of former President Clinton's nominees during the committee vetting process.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Republicans hold 55 seats in the 100-member Senate, and Vice President Dick Cheney, who also is president of the Senate, has said he will be available to break a tie, if necessary.</line><line>He offered that compromise on Thursday, 100 hours of debate on Circuit and Supreme Court nominees followed by a guaranteed confirmation vote.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>If the Senate is split 50-50 on the motion, the vice president will vote to break the tie and sustain his own ruling.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>&quot;I really think people on both sides don't want this to happen,&quot; said Sen. Joe Lieberman, D-Conn., one of those working for a compromise.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: What is a filibuster?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line><line>A: Republicans and Democrats anticipate that at least one of the nine Supreme Court justices will retire before the end of the Bush presidency.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Frist will bring up the nominations of Priscilla Owen and Janice Rogers Brown Wednesday through the Senate's regular operating rules, but a vote is unlikely to happen before next Tuesday or Wednesday, according to Frist's top aides.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Democrats argued that those judges were conservative ideologues.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Some polls have suggested that the American public is wary about the Republican push on federal judges.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Leaders on both sides said Tuesday they saw little room for a deal to avert the confrontation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>That did not discourage committee members from brushing aside Specter's plea for brevity and plunging into prolonged and angry debate about the two nominees.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>On Thursday, the Senate Judiciary Committee is expected to send a fifth nominee to the Senate floor -- William H. Pryor Jr., who was renominated by Bush to the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Dating from Bush's first term, Democrats have used a filibuster or the threat of extended debate, to block 10 of the president's choices for the federal appeals courts, while approving 35 others.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services at www.star-telegram.com) nn</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Republicans hold 55 seats in the Senate, meaning they can afford five defections and still triumph.</line><line>Officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said Democrats involved in the compromise would vote to end any filibuster blocking a final vote on Richard Griffin, David McKeague and Susan Neilson, all named to the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>&quot;The way she's been treated is less than humane,&quot; said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Frist's maneuver needs 50 votes to succeed, and while Republicans control 55 Senate seats, two senators have announced plans to side with the Democrats and at least half a dozen others are publicly undecided.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;We believe that every judicial nominee deserves an up or down vote,&quot; Rove said.</line><line>&quot;There would be no filibuster....</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>The confrontation is expected to play out over the coming week in stages and culminate early next week.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;We're going to support his proposal,&quot; Levin said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Earlier this year, Bush renominated seven of those who were blocked.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>The lead Democrat in the effort, Sen. Ben Nelson of Nebraska, told reporters that talks would continue.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Frist has promised to use a parliamentary maneuver that would outlaw those filibusters, in essence lowering the threshold for confirmation from 60 votes to 50 votes.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="5"><scu uid="30" label="Republican leaders threatened to rule out the filibuster [in judicial confirmations]." weight="2"/><scu uid="33" label="Nuclear option would effectively end/outlaw/rule-out filibusters" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>The presiding officer could seek the advice of the Senate Parliamentarian before sustaining the majority leader's point of order, but it is not required.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Neither side publicly discussed details of the Democratic offer.</line><line>&quot;I think Republicans are concerned that for the first time in history, a Supreme Court nominee might not get an up-or-down vote,&quot; said Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala.</line><line>&quot;Don't just focus on the past,&quot; Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., said.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="13"><scu uid="31" label="Frist was [Republican] Senate Majority Leader" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>&quot;I think that is most anathema to her Democratic critics -- they don't like the idea of articulate conservatives and they particularly don't like when it's a person of color,&quot; Wilson said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Several other Republicans are publicly uncommitted, and neither side appears certain it has enough votes to prevail if the issue is put to a vote.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>The precedent would apply to all federal judges, including the Supreme Court.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>&quot;This is an important and historic meeting,&quot; declared Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>A: Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, a Tennessee Republican, has never said when he would try to change the filibuster rules.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="6"><scu uid="30" label="Republican leaders threatened to rule out the filibuster [in judicial confirmations]." weight="2"/><scu uid="31" label="Frist was [Republican] Senate Majority Leader" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Three other nominations would continue to be blocked under the offer: those of Henry Saad to the 6th Circuit Court, Priscilla Owen to the 5th Circuit and William G. Myers III to the 9th Circuit.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>The talk of a compromise led to a Republican counteroffer proposed on the Senate floor by the chamber's No. 2 Republican, Majority Whip Mitch McConnell of Kentucky.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Both terms refer to pirates.</line><line>Those retirements usually come in the summer.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>&quot;I've tried to compromise and they want all or nothing, and I can't do that,&quot; Democratic leader Harry Reid of Nevada told reporters after a private meeting Monday with Majority Leader Bill Frist.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>&quot;She's waited four years for an up-and-down vote in the United States Senate.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>How can they do this?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>At her confirmation hearing Brown said she was not an ideologue of any stripe.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Senate rules require 60 votes to stop a filibuster, traditionally long-winded speeches designed to block or delay Senate action.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>After an hour and a half of discussions Tuesday evening that included Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., and Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., the meeting broke up with no progress reported.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Nelson also has spoken with Reid.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>The Senate is getting closer to a confrontation between Republicans and Democrats over whether President George W. Bush's judicial nominees can be filibustered by senators who don't want them confirmed.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="14,21,33,44"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>If a handful of Democrats broke with Reid, Nelson said, they could confirm some or all of the seven appellate court nominees thwarted by filibusters in Bush's first term and still awaiting action.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;The process is not well served by these political games.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist on Tuesday moved the chamber closer to a long-threatened showdown between Republicans and Democrats over President Bush's controversial judicial nominations.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="11,25,41,49,51"><scu uid="34" label="Frist's [Senate rule change/nuclear option] would also eliminate filibusters against Supreme Court nominees." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;There's a lot of finger-pointing going on on both sides,&quot; McConnell said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Rick Klein can be reached at rkleinglobe.com</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>&quot;We're in the ramp-up to a great constitutional crisis.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: Why don't Republicans keep the Senate in round-the-clock session to force Democrats to conduct the type of filibuster shown in Frank Capra's 1939 movie &quot;Mr. Smith Goes to Washington&quot;?</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>&quot;When you want to score, you run your best plays,&quot; said Senator George Allen, Republican of Virginia.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>An ABC/Washington Post survey published Tuesday suggested that two-thirds of Americans oppose Republican plans to change the filibuster rule and 26 percent support it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>&quot;I'm opposed to trying to eliminate filibusters simply because I think they protect minority rights, whether they're Republicans, Democrats or other people.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>The author of the majority opinion in the principal case, Justice Harriet O'Neill, wrote, &quot;In deciding this case we squarely confront the question of whether, as judges, we should apply the Parental Notification Act as it is written by the Legislature or according to our own personal beliefs.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>&quot;This fight is not about the seven radical nominations,&quot; Reid told reporters.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>With Democrats forming a solid wall of dissent, the Republican-dominated committee voted 10-8 to revive the long-dormant nominations of Priscilla Owen of Texas and Janice Rogers Brown of California.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="12,23,42"><scu uid="4" label="[Senate] Judicary Committee revived/approved/sent/released Brown's nomination" weight="2"/></annotation></line><line>Republicans have 55 votes, compared to 44 for Democrats and one for the lone independent senator, Jim Jeffords of Vermont.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>The Senate's Republican and Democratic leaders called for a prompt showdown in the impasse over judicial nominations Tuesday, a move that would undercut moderates' efforts to find a compromise to the long-running dispute.</line><line>If every effort has been made and fails, then they will be there&quot; when Frist calls for the showdown vote.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>The Tennessee Republican refused to comment on his way out of the meeting, but has said he will not take any deal that doesn't guarantee votes for all nominees on the Senate floor.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>The Senate will then vote on the motion, and a simple majority vote of the 100-member Senate will sustain the ruling of the presiding officer.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>As a result, Brown's confirmation battle is unlikely to reach the Senate floor until after Memorial Day.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="50" label="Brown's nomination would not reach the Senate floor until after Memorial Day [2005]." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Earlier this week, Sen. Harry Reid, the minority leader from Nevada, urged Frist to defuse tensions by proceeding with one of the less controversial nominees.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Frist also said he would offer Democrats a compromise before moving forward.</line><line>The outcome of the fight over judicial filibusters will determine whether a replacement needs 60 votes or merely a majority.</line><line>A: The Senate works at its current speed because much of its workload is handled through a procedure called &quot;unanimous consent.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Brown, who now serves on the California Supreme Court, was nominated to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in the District of Columbia, which deals with cases involving much of the federal government and is often described as second only to the Supreme Court in importance.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="10,22"><scu uid="6" label="Brown nomination was to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals of District of Columbia" weight="3"/><scu uid="13" label="Janice Rogers Brown is on the California Supreme Court" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>A: The filibuster is a parliamentary tactic where senators use their right to virtually unlimited debate to block measures or legislation.</line><line>That ruling would ultimately be submitted to the full Senate for a vote, with a simple majority required to prevail.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Frist's motion would establish a precedent, he said, under which all judicial nominations would get a vote after a certain amount of debate and confirmation would require 51 votes.</line><line>The nomination of California Supreme Court Justice Janice Rogers Brown to the federal appeals court in the District of Columbia also will be discussed in the coming days, but Republicans have decided to focus on Owen in their dispute with Democrats over judicial nominees.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="23,30"><scu uid="6" label="Brown nomination was to the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals of District of Columbia" weight="3"/><scu uid="13" label="Janice Rogers Brown is on the California Supreme Court" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Reid also asked that a bipartisan task force of retired senators be asked to make proposals on improving the judicial confirmation process.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Top Senate leaders declared an unsuccessful end to their compromise talks over President George W. Bush's stalled judicial nominees, despite fresh talk of a deal to clear five appeals court appointees while scuttling three others.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="3" sums="25,40,51"><scu uid="29" label="Senate leaders negotiated over judicial nominations procedure" weight="1"/><scu uid="39" label="Compromise was so far unsuccessful" weight="1"/><scu uid="39" label="Compromise was so far unsuccessful" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Conservatives are anxious for the rules to be changed before a Supreme Court vacancy, but Democrats have vowed to slow Senate business to a crawl in response.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>--- The presiding officer, who is likely to be Vice President Cheney, the president of the Senate under the U.S. Constitution, will sustain the majority leader's point of order.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Republican leaders have sent conflicting signals about which of the nominees they would likely bring to the floor first.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Frist, noting that four of the controversial nominations could be called to the Senate floor any time, told reporters that &quot;the suggestion has been made, let's go straight through the executive calendar and deal with them one by one.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>But a short while later, former California Gov. Pete Wilson appeared at the Republicans' weekly policy luncheon to brief his former Senate colleagues about Brown, who served for three years as his legal affairs advisor.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>They had lunch at the White House with Bush's chief counsel, Harriet Miers, dropped by the Oval Office for a brief visit with Bush and then made a carefully orchestrated appearance on Capitol Hill.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>A: Democrats oppose McKeague, Griffin and Saad, all nominees for the 6th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, because Republicans blocked Senate votes on former President Bill Clinton's nominees for vacancies on the same court.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="10,21,22,40"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Minority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., meanwhile, has said the right to filibuster must remain intact and President Bush must withdraw three of his most contentious appellate court nominees.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: Democrats have threatened to slow down the work of the Senate if Republicans succeed.</line><line>Republicans also say a round-the-clock filibuster debate wouldn't bring them any closer to a vote on the nominees themselves.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>Scott Shepard's e-mail address is sshepard@coxnews.com.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Reid said that although many Democrats oppose still him, they would not organize a filibuster against him.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>&quot;Every time you talk, you gain ground, you don't lose ground,&quot; Nelson said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>If the future of filibusters comes to a vote in the Senate, neither side is sure of the outcome.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;I believe my proposal strikes the right balance.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: Why is this important?</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>The two judges specified in Reid's offer -- Richard Griffin and David McKeague -- are among three nominees for the 6th Circuit in Michigan, a bench that has been the focus of partisan battles since the Clinton administration.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>But leading Democrats stood firm in their opposition to Owen.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>It was as he predicted, with each of the nominees receiving favorable votes from all 10 Republicans on the committee while all 8 Democrats voted against them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Democrats participated in the confirmation of about 200 judicial nominees.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="20,32,37,6"/></line><line>As soon as Democrats call a filibuster on one of them, Frist has said he will move to change the rules of the Senate to prohibit use of the procedure to block the confirmation votes.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="20,49"><scu uid="32" label="Republicans planed to use a parliamentary maneuver/&quot;the nuclear option&quot;" weight="2"/><scu uid="33" label="Nuclear option would effectively end/outlaw/rule-out filibusters" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>&quot;And if it's tough for the Democrats, that's fine with me.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>At the same time, if six Republicans and six Democrats agree to a compromise of their own, they could impose it on the leadership if necessary, averting a showdown.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Democrats used that power to scuttle 10 of Bush's 218 judicial nominees in his first term, and have vowed to do the same to defeat at least the seven he has re-nominated this year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist has cancer, raising questions about whether he will retire when the court session ends in June.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>However, a senior Democratic aide said Tuesday night that the two leaders left the meeting as far apart as ever, though that does not foreclose the possibility of rank-and-file members reaching an agreement on their own.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Frist declined to say which nominee he expected to bring up first for a vote -- a choice that would determine how rapidly the confrontation escalates.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Individual Democrats would be free to decide for themselves what constituted an extreme case for future nominees, according to officials familiar with the proposal.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>The proposed compromise, brokered by Nelson and Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., would be a pact between six Republicans and six Democrats to vote together to end filibusters of the stalled judicial nominees but also oppose any change in the rules permitting such filibusters.<annotation scu-count="5" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"><scu uid="35" label="Moderate Democratic and Republican senators tried to work out a compromise" weight="1"/><scu uid="36" label="Compromise would enable confirmation votes " weight="1"/><scu uid="38" label="Compromise would prevent &quot;nuclear option&quot;/[filibuster] rule change" weight="1"/><scu uid="40" label="[Six] Republican Senators and [six] Democratic Senators considered a pact" weight="1"/><scu uid="42" label="Pact was to defeat/prevent filibuster rule changes" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>Brown, who is black, is considered more likely to attract the support of independents and Republican moderates.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>If Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist of Tennessee decides to exercise the &quot;nuclear option&quot; to end a filibuster of President Bush's judicial nominees, here is how it is likely to unfold, motion by motion:<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="14,44"><scu uid="31" label="Frist was [Republican] Senate Majority Leader" weight="1"/><scu uid="34" label="Frist's [Senate rule change/nuclear option] would also eliminate filibusters against Supreme Court nominees." weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>But with party leaders and outside interest groups pressuring senators to stick with their caucuses, Nelson said, it may prove impossible to pass his proposal.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>As a result, many have expressed hope that a confrontation could be avoided.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>And if three more Republicans join the three who have vowed to oppose Frist's effort to ban filibusters of judicial nominees, the GOP leader would not have the 51 votes he needs to change the rule.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>For their part, Democrats would commit not to block votes on Bush's Supreme Court or appeals court nominees during the same period, except in extreme circumstances.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Frist is moving to confirm two female judges with compelling life stories, making it more difficult for Democrats to stand against them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>But Republicans said they were less concerned about current nominees than they were about future ones, especially an anticipated Supreme Court vacancy this summer.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="16"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Sen. Bill Frist of Tennessee, the Republican leader, has warned with increasing ardor that he may seek to change the rules so that the Democrats, who are in the minority, would be unable to block Bush's judicial choices.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>A senior Frist aide said Tuesday that Brown's nomination will move to the Senate floor after confirmation votes for Owen and John R. Bolton, Bush's nominee for U.N. ambassador.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Frist hosted Owen and Rogers Brown for a photo opportunity Tuesday at his office shortly after the two met with President Bush at the White House.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>&quot;But in an effort to work toward saving this institution...</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: Why do Democrats oppose these nominees?</line><line>Democrats filibustered 10 nominees to the U.S. appeals courts during Bush's first term, and they have said they will do so again this year for the seven that Bush renominated.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="33"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Bush's remarks to 1,500 donors attending a Republican Party fund-raising gala represented an escalation of the administration's campaign to pressure the Senate to act.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>&quot;I believe that we are skating over very thin ice here with regard to the continuity of life in the Senate as we've known it,&quot; Sen. Richard Lugar, an Indiana Republican, said over the weekend on CNN.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Under Reid's proposal, Republicans would have to withdraw the nomination of a third judge, Henry Saad, who has been stiffly opposed by Michigan's two senators, both Democrats: Sen. Debbie Stabenow and Sen. Carl Levin.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="16"><scu uid="29" label="Senate leaders negotiated over judicial nominations procedure" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Democrats are threatening to filibuster three of the four judicial nominees currently awaiting confirmation by the Senate.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="20"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>&quot;She deserves to be confirmed,&quot; said Sen. John Cornyn, R-Texas, a member of the committee.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>--- At this crucial point, the majority leader will offer a nondebatable motion to table the appeal from the minority leader.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Frist has said all along he will not accept any plan unless it gives each of Bush's nominees a yes-or-no vote.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>After being briefed about the compromise, Levin said he was willing to end his opposition to the two Michigan nominees if it would help Reid solve the conflict.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Afterward, Wilson said he believes Democrats are trying to &quot;demonize&quot; her, comparing her nomination to that of Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>The confrontation has been building for years as each party has used various methods to thwart the other party's nominations to the federal courts.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Democrats, in turn, say they have helped confirm 205 judicial nominees but object to a handful who are either unqualified or too extreme to hold life-time judicial appointments.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>In the hours before the parliamentary battle was to begin, the spotlight shone on a dozen or so centrists from both parties who discussed a potential compromise to defuse the dispute.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Republicans, who have a majority in the 100-member Senate, say the time has come to end what they describe as politically motivated obstructionist tactics by Democrats and sustain the president's right to send his nominees to the bench.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>In addition, Frist is under pressure from conservatives to ban filibusters before a vacancy arises on the Supreme Court, and the proposed agreement would not accomplish that.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>---The Senate will begin debate on one of the nominees, most likely Priscilla Owen of Texas or Janice Rogers Brown of California.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="23,29,32,55"><scu uid="11" label="Brown's nomination will go before the Senate" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Even Republicans who strongly opposed the Democrats' repeated use of filibusters argue that banning such moves would amount to a sweeping change in the way the Senate conducts business.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>In response, the Republican National Committee released results of internal polls that they said show that 81 percent of Americans believe Democrats should not block confirmation votes for judges even if they don't agree with them.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>All those votes require a simple majority, the aide said, and Cheney could break a possible tie.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Neither man could claim victory under compromises being promoted by Sen. Ben Nelson, D-Neb., among others.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>The rules change being considered by Senate Majority Leader Bill Frist, R-Tenn., would allow a simple 51-vote majority to end a filibuster.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="2" sums="19,48"><scu uid="30" label="Republican leaders threatened to rule out the filibuster [in judicial confirmations]." weight="2"/><scu uid="31" label="Frist was [Republican] Senate Majority Leader" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>In one dissent, Justice Owen said the teenager in the case had not demonstrated that she knew that there were religious objections to abortion and that some women who underwent abortions had experienced severe remorse.</line><line>A review of the court opinions shows that other judges also asserted that Owen and her fellow dissenters were putting their own views ahead of the law.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Under the deal, &quot;There'll be judicious use of the filibuster, and you won't have a nuclear option [a banning of filibusters] in this session of Congress,&quot; Nelson told reporters after the meeting.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Both sides acknowledge that the central issue is less the current list of nominees than the looming possibility of a Supreme Court vacancy later this year.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Republicans are expected to lose that vote, at which point Frist will begin the climactic chapter, according to his aide.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>A divided Senate Judiciary Committee on Thursday sent two controversial appeals court nominees toward a showdown vote in the Senate, setting the stage for what Democrats described as a looming &quot;constitutional crisis&quot; over President Bush's judicial nominations.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="11,29,41,49,55"><scu uid="4" label="[Senate] Judicary Committee revived/approved/sent/released Brown's nomination" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Sen. Sam Brownback, R- Kan., said the opinion showed Owen was &quot;actually following the Legislature's intent.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Reid denounced Rove's comments as an insistence that the Senate become a rubber stamp for the president by providing a &quot;100 percent confirmation rate.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>In his comments to reporters, Frist singled out Owen for praise, saying that &quot;it is just wrong that we do not allow her, after four years (since she was first nominated), that courtesy of an up-or-down vote.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>They also say at least two of Clinton's lower court judicial nominees were filibustered for years by Republicans, although they were ultimately confirmed.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Both are among the nominees most strongly opposed by organized labor as well as civil rights and abortion rights groups and others that provide political support for the Democratic Party.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>To stop a filibuster requires 60 votes.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>The chamber's uniqueness, they say, stems in part from the rights it preserves for the minority.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>A: It's more convenient merely to have a test vote to see if they have 60 votes and then move on to other issues if they don't.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>The American Bar Association gave Owen its highest recommendation in examining her qualifications for nomination.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>He offered to change committee procedures in return for an end to judicial filibusters.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>This individual spoke on condition of anonymity.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Frist said that Republicans &quot;have to look to the future to see that nominees for... the circuit court level and the Supreme Court have that opportunity for an up-or-down vote.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>The majority leader's point of order will maintain that further debate on the nomination is &quot;dilatory.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>She added that, &quot;The issue's highly charged nature does not excuse judges who impose their own personal convictions into what must be a strictly legal inquiry.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>The proposed compromise - being spearheaded by Nelson and Senator John McCain, Republican of Arizona - would probably be acceptable to Reid if it preserves Democrats' ability to filibuster judges in the future, according to aides to the Democratic leader.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Republican leaders said they would start the day's Senate session by fopening debate on President Bush's nomination of Texas Supreme Court Justice Priscilla Owen to the federal appeals court in New Orleans.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="13,29,43,55"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;I think that's in the back of everyone's mind.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>The agreement under discussion would bind the Republicans to preserving Democrats' right to filibuster judges, on the condition that Democrats only use filibusters in &quot;extreme circumstances,&quot; Nelson said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>However, a senior Democratic aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Reid offered to end filibusters on three of seven nominations stalled by Democrats -- two judges from Michigan and a third judicial nominee of Republicans' choice.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>&quot;Nothing has changed since we last reviewed her record to make Justice Owen worthy of confirmation now,&quot; said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Use of the term filibuster began to appear in the 1840s.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>Owen, a Texas Supreme Court justice nominated to the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans, has been held up for nearly four years amid Democratic allegations that she injected anti-abortion sentiments into her opinions and consistently handed down rulings that penalized consumers and favored big business.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Moderate GOP senators, Lott told radio talk host Tony Snow, &quot;have to feel assured that every avenue has been explored....</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>The second stage is expected to begin Friday, the aide said, when Republicans will file a motion to end debate on Owen.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>--- At some arbitrary point in the debate, the majority leader will seek a ruling from the presiding officer of the Senate &quot;regarding the appropriate length of time for debate&quot; on the nominee.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>But that left open the prospect that Democrats would filibuster Bush's other controversial nominees.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Without unanimous consent, it could take hours or days to complete work that now takes minutes.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>And I think it's time to do that.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>&quot;Our simple goal is to restore that 214 years of tradition to allow these nominees a simple, fair up-or-down vote,&quot; Frist said at a news conference.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Both parties' leaderships are wary of a bipartisan bid by a few centrists to find a middle ground that would force GOP and Democratic leaders to accept options they have called intolerable.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>It takes 60 votes to cut off a filibuster.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Democrats have said they will not delay vital legislation like appropriation bills and homeland security bills or money for America's troops.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>With Vice President Dick Cheney presiding over the chamber in his capacity as president of the Senate, Frist will make a motion suggesting that senators should have the right to vote on judicial nominees after a certain number of hours of debate have passed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Brown was assailed by Democrats over some of her judicial opinions but also over her many speeches in which she disparages the usefulness of government.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Brown and Thomas are both black.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Frist has threatened to change Senate procedures to strip them of their ability to do so.</line><line>At the same time, Republicans would be bound to leave filibuster practices in effect.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>They say the other four are conservative ideologues whose views against homosexuality, abortion, affirmative action, Social Security, labor rights or environmental standards are out of the mainstream.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Under Senate rules, as few as 41 senators can force unlimited debate through a procedure known as a filibuster, effectively killing a nomination.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>By their comments, the two party leaders pushed the Senate closer to a historic confrontation that could decide the fate of the appeals court candidates, Supreme Court nominees during Bush's term and the Senate's venerable filibuster rules as well.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="25,51"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>About a dozen senators met behind closed doors with Senate majority leader Bill Frist and Senate minority leader Harry Reid for about an hour late Tuesday afternoon to discuss the framework of the proposed compromise.<annotation scu-count="3" sum-count="1" sums="0"><scu uid="28" label="Reid was [Democratic] Senate Minority Leader " weight="1"/><scu uid="31" label="Frist was [Republican] Senate Majority Leader" weight="1"/><scu uid="35" label="Moderate Democratic and Republican senators tried to work out a compromise" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>For his part, Reid has not endorsed Nelson's proposal, which would clear the way for confirmation of one more judge than the party leader has publicly signaled he would accept.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>I would be willing to give up on any one of those five.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>&quot;All judicial and Supreme Court nominees deserve a fair up-or-down vote.&quot;<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Republicans say filibusters have never been successfully used to block judicial nominees from confirmation who had majority support.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="20,57"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., suggested that exploring compromises may help Frist gain the votes he will need to outlaw judicial filibusters.</line><line>Nelson said senators would have to pledge to use filibusters only in &quot;extreme or extraordinary cases.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Alberto R. Gonzales, the attorney general, who was a member of the court at the time, said the views of the dissenters were far beyond what the Legislature had enacted and amounted to &quot;an unconscionable act of judicial activism.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: Is this the first time judicial nominees have been filibustered?<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>As of Tuesday night, Frist remained on track to force the issue on the Senate floor, starting Wednesday morning.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="5"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Already, though, McCain and Sen. Lincoln Chafee of Rhode Island have said they will break ranks.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>However, it is expected that Republicans want the matter resolved before a retirement from the Supreme Court.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Reid said Democrats &quot;are prepared for a vote on the nuclear option.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Democrats accuse Bush and his Republican allies of breaking tradition by continuing to push for controversial choices.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>In recent years, Democrats used the filibuster -- in which a senator's right to extended debate is used as a stalling tactic -- to block votes on 10 of Bush's nominations to federal appellate courts.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="55"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>The debate about Owen has centered on her dissents from court rulings interpreting a state law allowing a minor to obtain an abortion without the permission of a parent in certain limited circumstances.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>Under the proposal, circulated in writing, Republicans would have to pledge no change through 2006 in the Senate's rules that allow filibusters against judicial nominees.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Times staff writers Mary Curtius, Richard Simon, Edwin Chen and Warren Vieth contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0342"><line>Still undecided, however, is the fate of eight men and women the White House has already nominated for judgeships and Democratic leaders have promised to filibuster.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>During Bush's first term, Democrats used the threat of a filibuster to block votes on 10 of his choices for federal appellate courts, charging the nominees were &quot;extremist&quot; in their conservative views.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="19,43,48"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>---The Senate would then be poised to vote on the judicial nominee.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0119"><line>Reid and Frist said they remain open to a possible compromise.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>Republicans accuse Democrats of breaking Senate tradition by resorting to the filibuster threat to block judges.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050517.0042"><line>&quot;We both agreed that after several months of discussions, we have been unable to come to a negotiated position where the president's nominees get an up-or-down vote,&quot; Frist said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Everyone understood that these candidates have come to stand for more than their own hopes to be confirmed; the two may be the test cases used by Republican leaders to change the Senate rules to prohibit filibusters to block judicial nominees.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050517.0198"><line>---A member of the Senate, probably Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid of Nevada, will object to the ruling of the presiding officer as contrary to the rules and precedents of the Senate, which currently require a vote of 60 senators to invoke cloture, that is, bring an end to debate.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0144"><line>The action propels the Senate toward a volatile, partisan confrontation, with Republicans contemplating a rules change that would prohibit further judicial filibusters and enable Bush to win Senate confirmation of his embattled court appointees.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>The filibuster was used in the 1950s and 1960s to impede civil rights legislation.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>This is the kind of judge we're looking for.&quot;</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>In the background of the debate was an anticipated Supreme Court confirmation battle this summer.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line><line>Senate Minority Leader Harry Reid, D-Nev., offered to end three of seven Democratic filibusters of President Bush's appellate court nominees if Republicans would pledge not to change Senate rules to end the use of the parliamentary tactic to stall votes on proposed judges.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="3" sums="16,3,35"><scu uid="28" label="Reid was [Democratic] Senate Minority Leader " weight="1"/><scu uid="29" label="Senate leaders negotiated over judicial nominations procedure" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Senate Democratic leader Harry Reid of Nevada also said Democrats might filibuster future nominees, possibly including Bush's choice for a Supreme Court vacancy should one occur.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="29,33"><scu uid="28" label="Reid was [Democratic] Senate Minority Leader " weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>Bush turned up the heat on the issue, saying Tuesday night that senators have &quot;a duty to promptly consider each of these nominees on the Senate floor, discuss and debate their qualifications, and then give them the up-or-down vote they deserve&quot; rather than filibuster them.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Both Owen, a justice on the Texas Supreme Court, and Brown, a justice on the California Supreme Court, have been blocked before by Democrats who have called them unfit for the federal bench, asserting that they are hard-line conservative ideologues.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050426.0147"><line>Democrats would also allow Republicans to vote on one of four remaining judicial nominees, all denounced by Democrats as conservative ideologues: Priscilla Owen, Janice Rogers Brown, William Pryor or William Myers.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="19"><scu uid="20" label="Democrats consider Brown's judical views extreme" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>The vice president can break 50-50 ties.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>&quot;Now is the time to address&quot; the judicial issue, Frist said at his weekly news conference.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050504.0186"><line>Q: When will Republicans do this?</line><line>Here, in question-and-answer form, is a look at some of the issues being debated:</line><line>Q: What do Republicans want to change?</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050510.0163"><line>&quot;We don't like any of those five,&quot; Reid said.</line></document><document name="LTW_ENG_20050517.0128"><line>&quot;Members on both sides don't want the explosion to occur.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050421.0254"><line>Sen. Arlen Specter, the Pennsylvania Republican who is the committee's chairman, asked his colleagues to be brief, saying there was little doubt that voting on the two candidates, Priscilla R. Owen and Janice Rogers Brown, would be along party lines.</line></document></collection>